(0,0)
$$ $0\le\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow (0,0)} \frac {|xf(y)+yf(x)|} {||(x,y)||}\le\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow (0,0)} \frac {||(x,y)||||(f(y),f(x))||} {||(x,y)||}$. The last expression is $\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow (0,0)} \frac {||(x,y)||||(f(y),f(x))||} {||(x,y)||}=\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow (0,0)} ||(f(y),f(x))||=||(f(0),f(0))||=0$. By the squeeze theorem, I can conclude that  $\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow (0,0)} \frac {|F(x,y)-(F(0,0)+<∇F(0,0),(x,y)>)|} {||(x,y)||}$=$0$, which means that $F$ is differentiable at the point $(0,0)$. 
